This comes after the cabinet discontinued the Zimbabwean Special Permit. But eligible Zimbabweans have been given a 12 month grace period. South Africa’s top diplomat remains cautiously optimistic that the country’s immigration laws will be fixed. Pandor says this will pave the way for the country to deal with its pressing matters around migration. Recently, the cabinet announced that Zimbabwe Special Permits will be discontinued. Pandor says this is a significant step in overhauling the system. “It is important that we do have proper immigration in the country to address all concerns that are out there some of the prejudices that are evident in some parts of our society,” says Naledi Pandor. --SABC--